# üîå Adapter Design Pattern

Adapter is a structural design pattern that allows incompatible interfaces to work together. ‚ÄúIt converts one interface into another that the client expects.‚Äù  
![The structure of the app before integration with the analytics library][image1]  
Adapters can not only convert data into various formats but can also help objects with different interfaces collaborate.   
Here‚Äôs how it works:

1. The adapter gets an interface, compatible with one of the existing objects.  
2. Using this interface, the existing object can safely call the adapter‚Äôs methods.  
3. Upon receiving a call, the adapter passes the request to the second object, but in a format and order that the second object expects.

Sometimes it‚Äôs even possible to create a two-way adapter that can convert the calls in both directions.  
![Adapter's solution][image2]

### Key Idea

* You have a class that doesn‚Äôt match the interface your code needs.  
* Instead of modifying it, you create an Adapter that makes it compatible.  
* Like a real-world plug adapter ‚Äî makes one thing fit another.

### What Problem Does It Solve?

* You want to reuse an existing class, but its interface is incompatible with your current code.  
* You can‚Äôt (or shouldn‚Äôt) modify the existing class (maybe it‚Äôs from a library or legacy system).

### How It Works

1. Define a target interface that your code expects.  
2. The existing class has a different method signature.  
3. You create an Adapter that implements the target interface and internally uses the existing class.

### When to Use

* You are integrating legacy code or external libraries.  
* You want to decouple the client from implementation details.  
* You want to follow Open/Closed Principle (open for extension, closed for modification).
